On 03/01/2022 at 2159 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Florence Yard (Florence, SC) discovered TILX112474, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated  and the shipper, Univar Solutions was notified. Marion Environmental Incorporated and HEPACO,  CSXT response contractors, responded and found the fill hole leaking from around a rolled gasket on  the fill hole The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Univar (Doug Nestler 408-221-4964). MEI corrected the fill hole gasket and reapplied the gasket  and secured the fill hole bolts tool tight. The tank car was released into transportation without  delay  Florence, SC – 03-01-2022 –TILX112474 – Hydrochloric Acid
column169: (NAR Code: 232 5 What Failed: Fill Hole Where Failed: Connection between fill hole nozzle and fill hole cover Why Failed: Gasket misaligned)

column168: 03/28/2022 at 10:26  hours, It was reported to H/M Scoons that in Pan AM Railroad yard ST RT%S Rotterdam, A DOT inspector discovered the MTZX33093 , a Loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the sample line valve in the  protective housing area. The car was isolated and AUX Sable Liquid Products, NYS DEC and NRC were notified. (CHEMTREC 2022-03-02-00231.  HM Scoons and HEPACO a CSX contractor responded and found the tank car was leaking from sample line valve. Upon inspection it was fond that the sample line valve was partially open and the secondary securement plug was less than tool tight and easily removed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Brad Brancato 851-715-0642 brad.brancato@auxsable.com. H/M Scoons and HEPACO personnel corrected the defects and secured the leak. Railcar car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.
column169: Describe: (NAR code:119 5 What Failed: Sample Line Where Failed: Closure plug Why Failed: Secondary Plug Improperly installed , valve open.

column168: Before uploading an aircraft, odor prompted an investigation. A small spill was cleaned and efforts made to determine what the inbound aircraft carried. At the cargo warehouse a shipment that had arrived on that flight awaiting transfer to a flight to LIH was determined to be the source. Each pail was marked "DOT Not regulated (reclassified as per 49CFR 173.150)" SDS indicated no other hazards, flash point of 105.8F, and no other means of transportation is practicable between Alaska and Hawai'i. Hence shipper reclassified the material as combustible liquid, and no longer "subject to the requirements of this subchapter."  Which would include 171.16, but FAA Hazmat has asked for the DOT Form 5800.1 report be filed.

On March 3, 2022, personnel at the above-referenced R+L Carriers (RLC) location discovered one (1) 30-gallon drum of UN1760 cleaning compound was missing its lid. As a result, approximately five (5) gallons of product released to the trailer interior. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to perform the necessary corrective action. ES personnel neutralized and absorbed all free product with soda ash and granular absorbents.

DescribePack: One of the bottles had a loose cap, which cause 0.5 Oz of the product to leak out DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: While wearing PPE, the product was wiped off and the cap was retighten.

SequenceEvent: Package was found in the damage hazmat area sitting inside a red bin. This package was loaded to the truck during the sort, and then brought back to us during the afternoon sort. I do know that this hazmat and along with a few more hazmats were sent down the three hundred van line during the morning sort. There really was no damage done to the product, besides the staining on the inside and the outside of the package. DescribePack: One of the bottles had a loose cap on it, which caused 1.50 ounces to leak out DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: While wearing the correct PPE, I wiped the  product off of the bottles and retighten the caps on all 4 bottles.

SequenceEvent: WHEN PACKAGE ARRIVED TO QA THE PACKAGE WAS WET FROM THE CORROSIVE LIQUID LEAKING OUT AND BREAKING DOWN BOX.THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A HAZMAT BAG AND PUT INTO A DRUM. THE PROPER PPE ATTIRE AND EQUIPMENT WAS USED IN SECURING HAZMAT. DescribePack: THERE WAS ONE OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS LEAKING FROM LOOSE CAP DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE LID WAS TIGHTENED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PUT INTO A HAZMAT BAG AND DRUM

SequenceEvent: The wet pkg was placed in a lined Hazmat tote upon discovery during sortation and was sent to QA where it was later moved to the Hazmat Processing Area. DescribePack: Loose caps and failed inner seals allowed liquid to leak wetting and staining the contents and carton. Staining on the outer carton is approximately 8" in circumference. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Pkg placed in lined Hazmat tote for damage inspection and processing.

column168: 1. E-2022030393 While traveling on Hwy 294 a tire on Veolia's trailer blew out causing the driver to pull over at the toll plaza. While inspecting the tire the driver noticed that liquid was leaking from the bottom of the trailer.  Upon inspection it was discovered that a drum on the trailer was squeezed and punctured in the middle of the drum. It is believed that while the shipper was loading the trailer, the forklift drum grabber squeezed the drum which led to the leak. The drum was overpacked so that it could continue safe transport to the destination.  2. E-2022030394 While traveling on Hwy 294 a tire on Veolia's trailer blew out and causing the driver to pull over at the toll plaza. While inspecting the tire it was noticed that some liquid was leaking from the trailer floor.  Further investigation revealed a drum on the trailer was punctured on the bottom causing liquid to leak out of the drum.  The cause of the puncture is unknown but it is suspected it was a nail. The leaking drum was overpacked so that it could safety resume transportation to the destination facility.
column169: 1. E-2022030393 The shipper was notified as this most likely occurred while loading the drums causing the drum to be dented by the forklift attachments.  The shipper will be reviewing their loading procedures and addressing this with the employees tasked with loading.    2. E-2022030394 Since it is inconclusive what caused this puncture it was reiterated to all Veolia drivers to sweep their trailer out prior to loading to reduce the risk of a container being punctured by loose debris on the floor of the truck.

While unloading a trailer at Veolia's facility in  Menomonee Falls, WI it was discovered that a 4G container was wet and had liquid mercury around it on the trailer floor.  Approximately .5 ounces of liquid mercury leaked out of the box.  The cause of the spill was due improper handling of the container it was loaded into the trailer.  Further investigation also revealed that the outer package was missing the inner liner when the inner containers were originally packaged.
column169: In the future, all packages will be inspected prior to loading to ensure the containers were packaged correctly. Veolia lab pack personnel have been asked to open the containers moving forward to verify the contents of each container prior to shipping them. This will ensure inner container integrity, packing media, and liners are present.   Loading procedure were also reviewed to ensure the packages are loaded properly and not handled inappropriately.  We believe this container was dropped while it was being loaded into the trailer prior to shipment.

column168: SOMEONE BROUGHT A LEAKING HAZMAT ON A BULK UNIT TO THE DMP. I DONNED FULL PPE, AND GOT MY SPILL CART AND DECISION TREE TO THE SPILL. I CLEANED UP THE SPILL ACCORDING TO THE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET AND DISPOSED OF THE REST ACCORDING TO THE WASTE DISPOSAL CHART.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET, LEAKING AND EMITTING A STRONG ALCOHOL ODOR BY THE SORTER ON BOXLINE-5. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP (APPROX. 12" RADIUS PUDDLE) AND THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WAS LOOSE BY A FULL ROTATION, CAUSING 2 QUARTS OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO AND OUT OF THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

A HAZMAT PACKAGE WITH SHIPPING PAPERS AND A CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL WAS WET WHEN IT GOT TO AN OUTBOUND AREA. A DESIGNATED RESPONDER INSPECTED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND THAT IT WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY DUE TO LOOSE CAPS ON THE BOTTLES INSIDE. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A LINED SPILL TUB AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: On 3/5/22, the GATX 80214 was found leaking while in the Interbay Railyard in Seattle, WA.  The car was isolated and BNSF Hazmat contractors responded to assess the release and impacts.  It was found that 2 liquid line flange bolts were loose contributing to a release of approximately 40 gallons of methanol.  Responders were able to secure the flange bolts stopping the release.  The car was cleaned and released methanol had evaporated.  Estimated release volumes are based upon observations of the responders in the field.  There were no injuries, exposures or impacts to waterways.  The car will move to destination on an OTMA requiring a bubble leak test for repairs.

The bubbly liquid coated the side of the drum. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Spill was absorbed with absorbent, bucket and cleanup kept in red bin lined with a large hazmat bag.

HAZMAT remained in a lined bin and was processed as a damage. DescribePack: The HAZMAT failed as the lid did not maintain adequate closure to contain product. Product leaked out through loosely secured lid. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin and then processed as a damage.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: SequenceEvent: Load manager called reporting a HAZMAT placed on the IC belt was actively leaking just after being placed on the belt, but was not dropped. The HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin and the area on the belt was dried with absorbent pad. On inspection, the HAZMAT was leaking from the bottom/side where a linear area was gouged out through and through consistent with scraping against a sharp object while being transferred from unload to the tugger, then to the belt. It remained in lined bin to contain drainage until it was processed as a damage. DescribePack: The body of the HAZMAT failed as a linear area was gouged out through and through from being scraped against a sharp object. The area gouged out measures 1.8mm x 4mm x 4mm. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The HAZMAT was removed from the belt and immediately placed in a lined bin to contain drainage. The belt was dried with absorbent pad.

column168: On 3-17-22, the WFRX 160368 was found by yard personnel to be leaking a small amount from the top of the car while being moved.  Crews isolated the car and made notifications.  BNSF Hazmat responders were called to investigate the release.  Upon arrival, the Responders identified that the leak was from the manway/nozzle surface.  Crews identified that 3 of the manway swing bolts were less than tool tight and easily moved by hand.  The manway gasket was inspected and replaced and the manway lid resecured.  Spilled ethanol was only observed on the sides of the car and quickly evaporated.  Release estimates are based on observations from the responders.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package fell of belt during unloading process causing lids to pop off and product to leak, QA was called to spill, package was put in lined tote and spill pads were used to clean up spilled product. DescribePack: Lids came off of cans during unload due to package falling off of belt. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was put in a lined tote.

SequenceEvent: Unload manager called QA with a leaking HAZMAT in the trailer. On inspection, the HAZMAT was on its side in opposition to the orientation arrows, wet, and crushed. On internal inspection, the drum was dented along the body, in 3 areas. The largest area also presented with a punctured area, and hence a site for drainage of contents. The HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin to contain drainage. Inner packing was adequate for transport. DescribePack: The HAZMAT failed as the body presented was damaged allowing for drainage of contents. It was significantly damaged along the central area of the body measuring 8in x 7in and a puncture site 3mm x 5mm. The other two sites where the body was damaged was just superior to the site noted above- both smaller and without a puncture site. The  box presented with damage consistent with the site of damage on the inner container. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin and processed as a damaged HAZMAT.

SequenceEvent: HAZMAT was brought to QA from load area as it was wet. On inspection, the top of the box was wet, but not otherwise damaged. Internal inspection revealed four (1) gallon bottles, each having loose lids and hence leakage of product. No internal partitions or protection to lids were noted. The HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin to contain contents. DescribePack: The HAZMAT failed when the lids lost the secure seal, resulting in leakage of product. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin to contain drainage then processed as a damage.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE FOUND WET, UPON INSPECTION PAIL WAS LEAKING FROM CAP/SEAL. PACKAGE CONTAINED, SPILLAGE ABSORBED. DescribePack: PAIL LEAKING FROM LOOSE CAP/SEAL. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE CONTAINED, SPILLAGE ABSORBED.

SequenceEvent: BOX WAS UNLOADED, BAGGED AND BROUGHT TO THE HWPA. DescribePack: THE BOX WAS WET ON THE TOP AND SIDE. INSIDE, BOTH BOTTLES LEAKED WHEN TILTED, ONE MORE THAN THE OTHER. NO HOLES, DEFECTIVE VALVE. NO SEAL UNDER CAP. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: HOLE WITH VALVE WAS PLUGGED AND TAPED OVER. CAPS RE-SCREWED. BOTTLES INDIVIDUALLY BAGGED.

SequenceEvent: BOX WAS UNLOADED,BAGGED AND TAKEN TO QA. HAZMAT SPECIALIST WAS NOTIFIED. BOX WAS TUGGED TO THE HWPA, BAGGED, IN A RED TOTE. DescribePack: THE BOX WAS DESTROYED ON ONE SIDE. THE BOTTLES LOOKED AS IF THEY WERE TAKEN OUT AND PUT BACK IN. INSIDE, 2 BOTTLES WERE DEPRESSED AT THE NECK, ALL OF THE SEALS ON THE BOTTLES WERE OPEN. ONE WAS ALMOST OFF, THE OTHERS HAD SMALL OPENINGS FROM 1/4 CM TO 1 CM. THE ORIENTATION ARROWS WERE NOT RESPECTED. ALL CAPS WERE ALSO LOOSE. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: EACH BOTTLE WAS INDIVIDUALLY BAGGED BEFORE BEING COLLECTIVELY BAGGED AND PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM.

SequenceEvent: Package was in trailer in unload. package handler was the wet haz-mat box and called QA for removal, QA removed haz-mat from trailer and placed it in a yellow  haz-mat tub. DescribePack: loose cap on jug. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: QA removed package from trailer and placed it in a yellow haz-mat tub.

SequenceEvent: Package arrived in the unload in this condition. Package was promptly placed into tote to await QA. I transferred the package to a lined red hazmat tote and took both totes to the damaged hazmat processing area. DescribePack: Inner bag failed at the top right corner when looking with the label facing up. The rupture in the bag was very small but enough to allow the chemical to leak out slowly. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Contaminated items removed from the area promptly to a well ventilated area with no employees nearby.

column168: On March 7, 2022 at 1300 ET, Landstar contacted ERTS regarding a UN1993, Flammable Liquid, 3 release that occurred at Solimex, 1708 Markley Lane, Laredo, TX.  E3 Response arrived onsite and confirmed that less than 10-gallons of product was released impacting a 53' x 12' area.  E3 advised that the tote was punctured by other freight during transit due to a load shift, the valve to be pushed in causing it to leak.  E3 generated (1) 55-gallon poly drum of impacted absorbents and PPE and was taken off site for disposal in addition to the damaged, empty tote.

It was advised that a 275-gallon tote was punctured by a forklift resulting in the release. At 0851 ET, the driver advised that up to 200 gallons of product were released and that facility personnel started working on the cleanup operations.  ERTS dispatched WEL Inc. to assist with the clean up.  At 1059 ET, WEL Inc. arrived onsite and began removing the soda ash and absorbent from the trailer that the terminal personnel applied to the impacted area.  Once completed waste was staged on site for disposal by the terminal personnel to handle.

column168: SequenceEvent: When I arrived to Qa3 at 0610 I was notified by a manager that a Hazmat had been damaged and was under the belt at work area 534. I obtained some gloves from the QA cage and a yellow salvage drum from the Hazmat cage and took it to where the hazmat was. I put on the gloves and placed the package in the yellow drum and carried it to the front of the belt where i had a push cart waiting. I loaded the salvage drum onto the cart and took it to the Hazmat Cage for storage until I had time to process it. DescribePack: Upon inspection I found that the bottom of the package had a hole of approximately 7" x 2". It appears this was caused by a leak of one of the 12 containers holding  1 quart of Sulfuric Acid each. The bottle that leaked had a loose cap that allowed its contents to spill out. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed in a hazmat bag to prevent more spillage

ALL REMAINING 18 OVERPACKS WERE INTACT WITHOUT INCIDENT. CRANE WORLDWIDE LOGISTICS, 10901 NW 146 STREET, HIALEAH GARDENS, FL 33018 IS THE FREIGHT FORWARDER WHO ARRANGED THE MOVEMENT OF THE SHIPMENT WITH UPS AIR CARGO SERVICE FROM MIA TO PVG. APPROPRIATE SHIPPERS DECLARATION PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER WITH PROPER MARKS AND LABELS. SPECIFICATION MARKINGS ON THE BAGS INSIDE THE OVERPACK ARE SHOWN AS 5M2/Z26/S/21/USA/M6316.

column168: On 03/23/2022 at 1158 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Sumter Yard (Sumter, SC) discovered TILX180096, a loaded tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S (Toluene, Acetone) leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, GEO Cycle, was notified via CHEMTREC. H/M James,  found the manway to be venting and a small amount of product on the side of the tank car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, George Colvin  662-272-6026, George.colvin@geocycle.com. H/M McCann removed the old manway gasket and  replaced it with a nozzle gasket and tightened the manway tool tight. The car was released back into  transportation without delay.

column168: On March 9, 2022 at 0820 hours, CN Mechanical employee observed a strong petroleum like odor near SHPX 213852 (Load / UN 2055 / Styrene Monomer, Stabilized / Class 3 / PG III) at CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, La.  The railcar was isolated, all required notifications made.  CN Response team responded and observed a strong petroleum like odor when approaching the railcar.  A drip leak was observed coming from the area of the bottom outlet valve. Liquid was observed streaming down the body of the bottom outlet valve and onto the ground. The cause of the release was determined to be that the bottom outlet valve handle packing gland bolts had backed out which allowed the packing gland to become dislodged from the valve body. The bottom outlet valve handle packing gland was pushed back into the valve body and the bolts were tightened, which secured the leak.  The railcar contents were transferred into another railcar.

column168: While breaking down freight in the LAX yard with a forklift, an employee punctured a 55-gallon drum of Pyrethrins banded to a wooden skid. The LAX Cargo team was able to contain the spill and the chemical did not reach any drains. Airport operations and environmental teams were contacted and the spill was cleaned up. LAWA and firefighters/paramedics were on the scene, documented the situation and we satisfied with containment.
column169: Root cause stem from situational awareness. As the agent was handling/moving several shipments containing the drums, the second shipment that was banded to a skid was different from the previous banded wooden skid. The inserts for the forklift blades were not that same due to the different skids that were used. The agent failed to adjust here forklift blades to appropriately fit the inserts of the wooden skid.     Corrective action: Coaching and agent required to take PIT training again for review.

column168: On March 29, 2022, one (1) 275-gallon tote of hydrofluorosilicic acid was punctured during transit and released approximately 150 gallons of product to the trailer interior. Free product further migrated to the concrete loading dock. R+L Carriers (RLC) retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to perform the necessary corrective action. ES personnel utilized soda ash to neutralize the free product, then deployed absorbents to remediate the impacted surfaces. Remaining product was transferred from the tote and the empty tote was collected for disposal.

column168: TEIX 2380 was found leaking in the BNSF Pearland yard on 3/16/2022.  BNSF Responder was dispatched to inspect TEIX 2380 and found the leak was from the bottom outlet valve where the valve attached to the car body.  The leak was remediated by transloading the car on site.  The defective bottom outlet connection was the cause of the leak.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package discovered on the dock during outbound sort preparation.  Box is in excellent condition.  Outer box had wet spots in a few spots and it had a smell to it.   Pulled package to QA to inspect. DescribePack: Box in excellent condition.  No outer issues other than visible wet spots.  Cans of lacquer thinner inside looked dented and the cap on one can did not seat down properly due to how the can was dented.  No inner packaging in the box.  Just metal on cardboard and then cans against each other. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Place package in plastic haz bag and then red haz tote.

SequenceEvent: Package was founded during  the unload and places into the a bin. DescribePack: the package failure due to the caps becoming loose. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: package was places into a red hazmat bin.

SequenceEvent: THE BOTTLE DIDN'T HAVE ANY SEAL TO PREVENT THE CAP FROM OPENING. DescribePack: THE CAP BECAME LOOSE CAUSING INTERNAL LEAKAGE. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: PKG WAS INSPECTED CAP WAS TIGHTRN DOWN.

SequenceEvent: Package was found leaking, QA was called to spill, neutralizer was used to clean up spilled product. Package was placed in a lined red tote DescribePack: Cap became loose during transit DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Cap was tightened and package was placed in a lined red tote

SequenceEvent: shipment taken out of system flow due external carton wet package came off trailer# 959226 already damaged wet and leaking package contained 4 x 1 gallon plastic bottles of low temp san one 1 gallon plastic bottle had a loose cap allowing .25 gallons to release package did have slotted partitions but no bags or absorbent was found. facility procedures for damaged hazardous materials followed contents contained and awaiting disposition DescribePack: one 1 gallon plastic bottle had a loose cap causing leakage and allowing .25 gallons to release DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: leaking package was placed in a hazmat bag lined tote

SequenceEvent: the cap came loose on one of the bottles of potassium hydroxide causing it to spill out of the packaging. when the package was duscovered it was placed in a bin and brought to qa for processing DescribePack: 1 loose cap DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: the package was placed in a bin to contain the spillage

SequenceEvent: Box was found in the Damages Area upside-down with its bottom open and top (with the label) wet.  The metal drum was upright within the box, however.  It was then put into the HazMat Cage within its red tote and HazMat bag for inspection. DescribePack: The bottom of the box was open - tape failed.  The top of the box was wet with label and OP-900 almost lost.  The metal pail within the box had two large dents.  The side is dented and the cap area is also dented.  The cap no longer functions and leaks worst closest to the dented area. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: It was moved into the HazMat Cage within a red tote and HazMat Bag.

SequenceEvent: The damaged package was placed in a hazardous material tote and taken to the hazardous material staging area away from personnel and other packages. DescribePack: Upon inspection it was noted that one of the plastic jugs of Colorwright stain had a pinhole leak at the bottom causing the contents to leak. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The damaged package was placed in a hazardous material drum awaiting disposition.

SequenceEvent: LOOSE CAP AND SEAL CAUSING LEAKAGE OF CONTENT IN PACKAGE. PLACED IN A RED HAZMAT TOTE DescribePack: LOOSE CAP AND SEAL FROM BOTTLE DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PLACED IN RED HAZMAT TOTE

SequenceEvent: LOOSE CAP AND SEAL, CAUSING LEAKAGE OF CONTENT IN PACKAGING. PLACED IN RED HAZMAT TOTE TO CONTAIN SPILLAGE DescribePack: LOOSE CAP AND SEAL FROM PACKAGE DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PLACED IN RED HAZMAT TOTE

SequenceEvent: QA was retaping packages in the unload when they stumbled upon several hazmats in the wrong orientation on the NC rollers. QA noticed that there was one hazmat that was leaking so they put the hazmat in a hazmat tote and cleaned up the liquid with proper ppe. QA transported the hazmat to the hazmat cage for further inspection where it was determined that due to the orientation arrows being disrespected, the cap had slightly loosened up causing minimal leakage. DescribePack: Due to the orientation arrows being disrespected, the cap slightly loosened up causing it to leak inside and outside the package DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: QA cleaned up the spill with proper ppe.

SequenceEvent: The box was found wet in the unload and moved to the hazmat cage for reports. DescribePack: The cap on 1 of the jugs in the box was loose and leaked about 16 oz. of contents.  The seal under the cap did not stop the leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The box was placed arrows up into a hazbag lined tote.

SequenceEvent: WHILE A PACKAGE HANDLER WAS UNLOADING A  TRAILER HE NOTICED THAT A PACKAGE WAS ON IT DISE AND WAS LEAKING, HE TOLD HIS MANAGER. DescribePack: THE PACKAGE WAS ON HIS SIDE AND SPILLED OUT FROM THE CAP  ABOUT ONE LIQUID POUND  OR MORE. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE MANAGER CALLED QA AND QA GRAB A RED TOTE LINSE WITH A HAZMAT BAG AND SOME LOOSE ABSORB AND WENT TO THE AREA TO INVESTIGATE THE SITUATION.  QA PUT THE PACKAGE IN THE TOTE AND ALSO HE GRAB  THE  ON THE SIDE BECAUSE GOT A WET SIDE.  WE BROUGHT BOTH TO PACKAGES TO THE PROCESSING CAGE.

SequenceEvent: The belt manager brought this over to us after it was loaded on to the van after the Package handler noticed some leaking on top of the box. He brought the package over to QA 2 at 7:30 am. We inspected the package and there were 3 bottles that all had loose caps and compromised foil seals which lead to the leaking. The package was put into a lined hazmat tote and taken to the hazmat cage. DescribePack: 3 caps were loose and the foil seals were compromised DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was immediately removed from the van then put into a lined hazmat tote and separated from the other packages.

column168: On March 4, 2022, at 2015, XPO Logistics Terminal XCN reported 70-gallons of UN1824 "Quakerclean 7001 MC" released on the dock from a 330-gallon poly tote that was punctured by a forklift. Terminal personnel flipped the tote to stop the release. ERTS dispatched HEPACO to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 2238 ET, HEPACO personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 70-gallons of product released to a 10'x10' area of the dock floor. HEPACO transferred the remaining product into a new tote and cut up the damaged tote. Absorbent were worked into the impacted area, then collected and containerized the cut up damaged tote and clean up debris into four 55-gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On March 12, 2022 at 1545 hrs., CN Transportation crews reported liquid coming down the sides of UTLX 630833 (Load / UN 1824 / Sodium Hydroxide Solution / Class 8 / PG II ) at CN Gladstone Yard, Gladstone, MI.  The railcar was isolated, all required notifications made.  CN Response team responded and observed liquid on the side of the railcar near the side ladder access.  Upon closer inspection, when climbing the railcar, liquid was observed coming down the railcar manway nozzle, then onto the sides of the railcar.  The manway swing bolts were checked and found to be tool tight and secured by a security seal.  The security seal was removed and the manway opened.  The manway gasket was found to be misaligned. A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway swing bolts were properly tightened, which secured the leak.  The exterior of the railcar was decontaminated, then released onto destination.

A pallet with 4 metal drums was double stacked in van trailer behind the affected tote. The double stacked pallet broke allowing the drums to fall from a level of approx. 4 feet landing on the partially filled tote causing the aluminum cage to give way and the poly tote to be crushed resulting in a breech of the poly tote allowing material contained in the tote to spill.
column169: Remedial training and coaching will be implemented regarding inspection of drums being used to secure material. The driver will also be remediated regarding his/her  responsibility to thoroughly inspect the load for securement and be observant of the quality and appearance of visible pallets, especially for those that are double stacked.

column168: On March 14, 2022, Landstar Ranger called to report an unknown amount of UN1993 SCL 8054 releasing when a driver swerved to avoid an accident and the swerve caused a tote on the trailer to fall out of the trailer and onto the roadway.  Allied arrived on site and located the tote and the impacted areas.  The first area impacted measured 1' by 1'  on the roadway, the crew spread absorbents over the area.  The soil was impacted in two areas 60' by 1' and 10' by 6', which was secured with poly sheeting and boom to be excavated at a later date. The team recovered 200-gallons of product, and material was transferred into (4) 55-gallon steel drums.  Allied departed the site.  On March 30, 2022, Allied return to the site for excavation and backfill operations.  Post excavation dimensions were 14' in length by 12' in width to a depth of 5-inches below original grade.    Operations completed Allied left the site.

column168: On 03/23/2022 at approximately 21:00 hours CST a CN Mechanical employee observed vapor coming from the top of tank car TILX 112804 (Loaded / Hydrochloric Acid/ UN 1789/ Class 8/ PGII) at the CN Kirk Yard (Matteson Subdivision M.P. 0.57) in Gary, IN. The railcar was isolated and required notifications made.  CN response team responded and also observed vapors coming from the top of the railcar.  The investigation performed by the CN response team found one of the pressure plate securement fasteners was not properly tightened allowing vapor to be released from the loose pressure plate securement fastener location. The fastener was tightened with an 18" adjustable wrench, which stopped the leak. The exterior surface of the tank car was decontaminated with a liquid base solution.

column168: Driver arrived at customer site began the setup for the loading of his tank. Driver checked his domes, and checked the equipment.  He set the hoses, walked them twice , then hooked up, started the engine and opened the travel valve.  No vacuum.  When Driver went to trouble shot his tanker, he opened the sample port. A small amount of residual product misted out and onto containment tray.  Valve was closed immediately.  Opening the travel valve caused pressure rather than vacuum.  Both driver and loader immediately contacted in-site Intel supervisor, and in-site Hazardous Waste Department.  The spilled waste was contained within the containment tray and was cleaned up by plant technicians. Tanker was swapped out at the request of a attending Intel employee. Load was completed after the changes had taken place without issue..
column169: Retraining on tanker procedures to prevent future events.   Port valve must have bucket underneath to catch any residual spillage.  Additional emergency equipment to be carried with each load/unload and will include bucket and lid.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Incorrectly Sized Component or Device
column168: During switching operations at NS yard in Lynchburg, VA tank car TCBX 196196 was observed with liquid running down from the top of the car anytime it was moved.  The liquid had a strong alcohol smell and evaporated quickly.  The car was setout and a response contractor was called to investigate the leak.   Hepaco responded and investigated the source of the leak.  Hepaco opened the manway and found the lid gasket was not properly installed and was in a deteriorated condition.  The manway lid gasket was not properly seated in the lid groove and a portion was sticking out allowing product out.  The gasket was either the wrong size or stretched out.    A new nozzle gasket was installed and the car was resealed.

Spilled material was subsequently collected and the contents of the supersack were transferred into a new supersack. Media affected was limited to trailer flooring components. column168: The driver had just left Green River Bulk Plant at 7:35 am heading to make deliveries and turned north on Hwy 136.     He traveled approximately 2 miles at a speed of 50-55 mph.  At7:45 am, he met a car traveling southbound that crossed the center yellow line into his lane. At that instance, he reacted by moving over to the right and dropped  off shoulder of road.  He stayed off the road trying to maintain the Slip Off/Stay Off maneuver.   After traveling 184 ft, he approached a guard rail and bridge.   At that point, he swerved the bobtail to the left back on to the road crossing the southbound lane.    This maneuver caused the back end of bobtail to slide to the left going off the left side of the Hwy.  The edge of the asphalt road gave away under the weight of the truck causing the truck to strike the guard rail with the rear of the truck going into a steep embankment while the front end of the truck was still on the road.  This action pulled the front of the truck into the steep embankment.  He traveled 50ft until he was able to stop the truck.  The truck was stopped on a steep embankment was full of propane which made the truck top heavy.  The truck then rolled on to the driver’s side.  He driver exited the vehicle from the passenger side.   As soon as the driver exited the vehicle, the truck turned over, rolled down the steep embankment, and came to rest on the passenger side. A passing motorist, that did not observe the accident, called 911 for assistance.  The local Fire Department and Sherriff Department responded and secured the accident scene. The driver was taken to the hospital by his wife.  He was release with no injuries or treatment and driven back to the scene. A wrecker service arrived on scene, lifted the vehicle on to the road and towed back to the Green River Facility
column169: The Lytx camera system will be installed to better capture future events.  90-Day Probationary Period: The Driver has been assigned to a truck having a Lytx camera installed to monitor his driving performance.  DM will perform and document ride along assessment at 30, 60, and 90 day intervals.  Safety Flash will be developed and sent to the entire organization.

column168: PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE ATTENTION OF A SPILL SPECIALIST AT OUR ANCHORAGE, ALASKA LOCATION. DURING THE COURSE OF NORMAL SORT OPERATIONS, THIS PACKAGE SHOWED LEAKING FROM THE CORNERS OF THE BOX. INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE FOUND THIS PACKAGE WAS PART OF A MULTI PIECE SHIPMENT. PACKAGE WAS PACKED IN A FIBREBOARD BOX. THE BOX CONTAINED 4 METAL CANS CONTAINING 3.78L OF UN1263. EACH CAN WAS FITTED WITH A RING LOCK AND PLACED ON THE LOWER LEVEL OF THE BOX SEPARATED BY FIBREBOARD DIVIDERS BETWEEN THE CANS. THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE REPORTED ON THE LOWER LEVEL OF THIS BOX TO CUSHION CANS. ON TOP OF THE LOWER LEVEL, SHEETS OF FIBREBOARD WAS PLACED SO 4 METAL CANS CONTAINING 1L OF UN1263 COULD BE ADDED TO THE TOP LAYER. EACH CAN WAS FITTED WITH A RING LOCK TO HOLD THE LID IN PLACE AND WERE SEPARATED BY FIBERBOARD DIVIDERS. THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE REPORTED ON THE TOP LAYER OF THIS PACKAGE. THERE WAS 20L TOTAL OF COMMODITY DECLARED. THERE WAS NO MOISTURE BARRIER REPORTED USED IN THIS PACKAGE. THIS PACKAGING WAS MARKED WITH 3 UN SPECIFICATION MARKINGS WHICH WOULD BE DETERMINED BY THE MANUFACTURER CLOSING INSTRUCTIONS AND TESTING WITH INNER CONTENTS, HOWEVER, CARRIER DG SPECIALIST CANNOT DETERMINE WHICH CLOSING INSTRUCT WAS USED. BASED OF METAL CANS ON THE LOWER LEVEL SHOWED DAMAGE ON THE BOTTOM CHIMES AND BOTTOM OF ALL CANS. IT WAS REPORTED AT LEAST 2 CANS SEEM TO SHOW LEAKAGE. ONE OF THE SMALLER CANS SEEM TO SHOW LEAKAGE FROM THE LID AREA.  IT IS NOT KNOWN HOW THE INNER CONTENTS WERE DAMAGED. PACKAGED WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE PACKAGE AND EMPLOYEES INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT SHIPPER FOR AN AMENDED SHIPPERS DECLARATION AS FEDEX POLICY DOES NOT ALLOW FOR THE SHIPMENT OF SALVAGE PACKAGES TO INTERNATIONAL LOCATIONS.

column168: At approximately 1:26pm, an employee loading inside the trailer on bay door 232 noticed a package on fire sitting on the rollers. The employee exited the trailer and reported the fire to his supervisor. The supervisor entered the trailer with a fire extinguisher and extinguished the fire out. Shortly after, the package was removed from the trailer and it was brought over to the damage material processing area where the package could be secured and inspected safely. The ground limited quantity package contained 12 aerosol adhesive spray cans in which 4 of the 12 spray cannister caps were damaged due to the fire. The inner carton showed adhesive residue inside the box along with evidence of scorching.
